article.headline: Creighton improves to 7-0 with 33-point victory
article.linkText: Ranked for first time in 27 years, Creighton rolls
article.story:
OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Ranked for the first time in 27 years, the
Creighton Bluejays certainly played like a Top 25 team in an easy
victory over Tennessee Tech.

	   Kyle Korver hit six 3-three pointers and had 20 points as 
Creighton (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) remained unbeaten with a 101-72 victory Saturday night.

	   ''We didn't want to be one-week wonders,'' Korver said of the
Bluejays' first national ranking since 1975.

	   Joe Dabbert added a career-high 17 points, Larry House had 13
and Brody Deren 12 for Creighton.

	   The Bluejays are 7-0 for the second time in four seasons and the
11th time in the program's 85-year history.

	   The Bluejays topped 100 points for the second time this season.
They opened the season with a 106-50 win over Texas-Arlington, and
have an average winning margin of 26.4 points.

	   ''A lot of these games have been at home,'' Korver said. ''I
don't want to talk us up too much because we've got some big games
coming up.''

	   Korver, 6-of-9 shots from 3-point range, said he likes the
chemistry that has developed so far for the Bluejays, who have been
to four straight NCAA Tournaments.

	   ''It's by far the best since I've been here,'' Korver said. ''If
things keep going like they have, we can be good.''

	   Creighton outscored the Golden Eagles 17-0 over a 5:38 span of
the first half to break open the game.

	   Joe Dabbert had nine of his 11 first-half points during the
decisive run, which turned Creighton's 7-5 lead into a 24-5 bulge.
Tennessee Tech, facing intense defensive pressure, committed five
turnovers on six possessions and went scoreless on nine straight as
the Bluejays pulled away.

	   ''The first half we played as well as we could play,'' Creighton
coach Dana Altman said. ''That's the best half we've played this
year.''

	   Dabbert, benched for poor play in Creighton's previous game,
against Brigham Young, made 6-of-8 shots while scoring his 17
points -- all in 15 minutes of action.

	   Damien Kinloch had 19 points and 10 rebounds to lead Tennessee
Tech (4-3). Kyon Boyd added 12 points and Milone Clark had 10.

	   Creighton, which led 50-27 at halftime, was up by 24 points on
three occasions in the first half.

	   House had seven points and Korver six as the Bluejays opened the
second half on a 15-2 run. House finished the spurt with a
3-pointer that gave Creighton its biggest lead of the game at
65-29.

	   ''It was just one of those nights where we got going and then
the crowd got into it,'' Altman said.

	   Creighton outrebounded the Eagles 34-33. Tennessee Tech entered
the game having outrebounded its previous six opponents by an
average of 11.3 a game.

	   The Bluejays held Tennessee Tech to 43.3 percent shooting from
the field, and they forced 21 turnovers.

	   ''Creighton played like a nationally ranked team,'' Eagles coach
Mike Sutton said. ''They beat us in every facet of the game.''
